th.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: nums = [2,6,4,8,10,9,15]\nOutput: 5\nExplanation: You need to sort [6, 4, 8, 10, 9] in ascending order to make the whole array sorted in ascending order.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums = [1,2,3,4]\nOutput: 0\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: nums = [1]\nOutput: 0\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 104\n-105 <= nums[i] <= 105\n\n \nFollow up: Can you solve it in O(n) time complexity?\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def findUnsortedSubarray(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def findUnsortedSubarray(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Create a sorted version of the array to compare with\n        sorted_nums = sorted(nums)\n        \n        # Initialize variables to track the start and end of the subarray\n        start = -1\n        end = -2\n        \n        # Iterate through the array to find the first and last mismatch\n        for i in range(len(nums)):\n            if nums[i] != sorted_nums[i]:\n                if start == -1:\n                    start = i\n                end = i\n        \n        # The length of the subarray to be sorted\n        return end - start + 1\n```\n\nThis solution works by comparing the original array with its sorted version. It identifies the first and last positions where the elements differ, which indicate the boundaries of the subarray that needs to be sorted. The time complexity of this solution is O(n log n) due to the sorting step.\n\nTo achieve the follow-up requirement of solving it in O(n) time complexity, we can use a different approach:\n\n```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def findUnsortedSubarray(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        n = len(nums)\n        max_from_left = float('-inf')\n        min_from_right = float('inf')\n        \n        # Initialize variables to track the start and end of the subarray\n        start = -1\n        end = -2\n        \n        # Iterate from left to right to find the end of the subarray\n        for i in range(n):\n            max_from_left = max(max_from_left, nums[i])\n            if nums[i] < max_from_left:\n                end = i\n        \n        # Iterate from right to left to find the start of the subarray\n        for i in range(n - 1, -1, -1):\n            min_from_right = min(min_from_right, nums[i])\n            if nums[i] > min_from_right:\n                start = i\n        \n        # The length of the subarray to be sorted\n        return end - start + 1\n```\n\nThis optimized solution uses two passes through the array to determine the boundaries of the subarray that needs to be sorted. It keeps track of the maximum value from the left and the minimum value from the right, updating the start and end indices accordingly. This approach ensures an O(n) time complexity.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}